/speckit.tasks

Use the HAVEN Architecture Constitution and the approved /speckit.plan as the source of truth.

You are now generating an implementation task breakdown for a Kubernetes-native, GitOps-driven microservices platform.

---

# 1. Objective

Transform the system plan into a **detailed, execution-ready engineering backlog**.

Each task MUST be:

- atomic (single responsibility)
- independently verifiable
- implementation-ready
- mapped to a specific system component
- aligned with GitOps delivery

---

# 2. Scope

Generate tasks for the full HAVEN platform:

## Services
- Service A (API Orchestrator)
- Service B (Domain + PostgreSQL service)

## Platform Components
- Keycloak (OIDC provider)
- PostgreSQL
- NGINX Ingress Controller
- cert-manager (Let’s Encrypt)
- FluxCD (GitOps)
- Terraform (infrastructure provisioning)
- Observability stack (Prometheus / OpenTelemetry)

---

# 3. Task Structure Requirements

Each task MUST include:

- Task ID (unique)
- Title
- Component (Service / Platform / Infra)
- Description (clear implementation intent)
- Dependencies
- Acceptance Criteria
- Verification Method
- Compliance Tags:
  - 15-factor
  - security
  - gitops
  - observability
  - kubernetes
  - terraform (if applicable)

---

# 4. Task Grouping

Organize tasks into the following epics:

## EPIC A — Infrastructure Foundation (Terraform)
- Kubernetes cluster provisioning
- Networking setup
- DNS configuration
- Keycloak deployment
- cert-manager installation
- NGINX ingress installation

---

## EPIC B — Identity & Security Setup
- Keycloak realm configuration
- OAuth2 clients for Service A and B
- Role/scope definitions
- JWT validation configuration
- Secret management strategy

---

## EPIC C — Core Services Implementation
### Service A
- Spring Boot project bootstrap
- REST API implementation
- OAuth2 client integration
- WebClient service-to-service calls
- Observability integration

### Service B
- Spring Boot project bootstrap
- REST API implementation
- PostgreSQL integration
- Flyway migration setup
- OAuth2 resource server configuration

---

## EPIC D — Data Layer Implementation
- PostgreSQL provisioning
- Schema design per service
- Migration pipeline setup
- Data isolation enforcement

---

## EPIC E — GitOps & Deployment (FluxCD)
- Git repository structure setup
- FluxCD bootstrap configuration
- Kustomize/Helm deployment definitions
- Environment overlays (dev/test/prod)
- Automated reconciliation setup

---

## EPIC F — CI/CD Pipeline
- Build pipeline definition
- Docker image build process
- Security scanning integration
- Artifact versioning strategy
- GitOps commit-based deployment flow

---

## EPIC G — Observability Implementation
- Metrics instrumentation (Micrometer)
- Logging standardization (JSON structured logs)
- OpenTelemetry tracing setup
- Prometheus scraping configuration
- Correlation ID propagation

---

## EPIC H — Kubernetes Runtime Configuration
- Deployment manifests
- Service definitions
- Ingress rules
- TLS configuration via cert-manager
- Resource limits and HPA configuration
- Network policies

---

## EPIC I — Resilience & Reliability
- Timeout configuration per service call
- Retry policies
- Circuit breaker implementation
- Failure handling strategies
- Graceful degradation patterns

---

# 5. Dependency Rules

- Infrastructure MUST precede all service deployment tasks
- Keycloak MUST be available before service security configuration
- PostgreSQL MUST exist before Service B implementation
- FluxCD MUST be configured before deployment tasks
- Observability must be integrated after service skeleton creation but before production readiness

---

# 6. Execution Order Constraint

Tasks MUST be ordered by dependency chain:

1. Terraform infrastructure
2. Platform services (Keycloak, ingress, cert-manager)
3. Observability foundation
4. Service scaffolding
5. Security integration
6. Data layer
7. GitOps deployment
8. Hardening (resilience, policies, scaling)

---

# 7. Compliance Rules

Every task MUST comply with:

- HAVEN Architecture Constitution
- 15-factor cloud-native principles
- GitOps-only deployment model
- Zero manual production configuration
- Strict service ownership boundaries

---

# 8. Output Format

Return tasks in the following structure:

## Epic Name

### Task ID: HAVEN-XXX
- Title:
- Component:
- Description:
- Dependencies:
- Acceptance Criteria:
- Verification:
- Compliance Tags:

---

# 9. Final Requirement

The output MUST be directly usable to:

- create GitHub issues
- populate project boards
- drive engineering sprint planning
- map to CI/CD execution pipelines

No abstract or non-actionable tasks are allowed.